│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The IR triggers a crash in instcombine while attempting to fold a             │
│ shufflevector into a preceding vector-select. The select condition is a <2 x  │
│ i1> vector, while the shufflevector result is a <4 x float> vector.           │
│ InstCombine's FoldOpIntoSelect tries to manufacture a new Select with the     │
│ original condition and newly folded arm values. This leads to constructing a  │
│ Select whose condition vector length does not match the result vector length, │
│ violating IR rules and hitting the assertion in SelectInst::init.             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - The first transformation point is SelectInst::Create invoked by             │
│ FoldOpIntoSelect.                                                             │
│ - The call path is visitShuffleVectorInst -> FoldOpIntoSelect.                │
│ - The LHS of the shuffle is the select, and RHS is a constant                 │
│ (zeroinitializer). The mask increases the vector length from 2 to 4.          │
│ - The instcombine debug log shows it visits the select and then the shuffle,  │
│ and immediately aborts when building the new select.                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ FoldOpIntoSelect assumes it can create a new select using the existing        │
│ condition SI->getCondition() and the newly folded true/false values derived   │
│ from applying the operation to each arm. However, SelectInst in LLVM          │
│ requires:                                                                     │
│ - The condition to be i1 for scalar selects.                                  │
│ - For vector selects, the condition must be a vector of i1 with the same      │
│ number of elements as the result vector.                                      │
│ In this case, SI->getCondition() is <2 x i1>, but after folding the shuffle   │
│ into each arm, NewTV/NewFV are <4 x float>. SelectInst::Create is called with │
│ mismatched vector lengths, triggering the assertion. There is no guard in     │
│ FoldOpIntoSelect to ensure the condition/result element counts match when the │
│ operation changes vector length.                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ We need to add an early bailout in FoldOpIntoSelect when folding would        │
│ produce a select whose result type has a different vector length than the     │
│ select's condition. Specifically, if SI's condition is a vector type, require │
│ that Op's result is also a vector type with the same element count. If not,   │
│ do not fold.                                                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit at llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp lines        │
│ 1696-1706 (right after the existing checks that the select arms contain       │
│ constants and the bool select early return):                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ Insert the following guard:                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│   // If the select condition is a vector, its length must match the           │
│   // result vector length of the folded operation. Otherwise, creating        │
│   // a new select with the original condition and the folded arm values       │
│   // would be invalid.                                                        │
│   Type *OpTy = Op.getType();                                                  │
│   Type *CondTy = SI->getCondition()->getType();                               │
│   if (CondTy->isVectorTy()) {                                                 │
│     auto *CondVTy = cast<VectorType>(CondTy);                                 │
│     if (!OpTy->isVectorTy())                                                  │
│       return nullptr;                                                         │
│     auto *OpVTy = cast<VectorType>(OpTy);                                     │
│     if (CondVTy->getElementCount() != OpVTy->getElementCount())               │
│       return nullptr;                                                         │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale:                                                                    │
│ - This prevents attempting to create a select with mismatched                 │
│ condition/result vector lengths when the operation (e.g., shuffle) changes    │
│ the vector length.                                                            │
│ - It preserves existing, valid cases (scalar condition, or matching vector    │
│ lengths), and continues to allow folding of operations that do not change the │
│ vector length.                                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is caused by FoldOpIntoSelect creating an invalid Select when       │
│ folding a length-changing vector operation (shufflevector) into a             │
│ vector-select with a shorter condition. Adding a guard to bail out when the   │
│ condition is a vector and its element count differs from the folded           │
│ operation's result vector length prevents the invalid Select construction and │
│ fixes the assertion. This maintains correctness without affecting other       │
│ folding opportunities.                                                        │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
