  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe IR triggers a crash in
instcombine while attempting to fold a shufflevector into a preceding
vector-select. The select condition is a <2 x i1> vector, while the shufflevector
result is a <4 x float> vector. InstCombine's FoldOpIntoSelect tries to
manufacture a new Select with the original condition and newly folded arm values.
This leads to constructing a Select whose condition vector length does not match
the result vector length, violating IR rules and hitting the assertion in
SelectInst::init.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The first transformation point is
SelectInst::Create invoked by FoldOpIntoSelect.\n- The call path is
visitShuffleVectorInst -> FoldOpIntoSelect.\n- The LHS of the shuffle is the
select, and RHS is a constant (zeroinitializer). The mask increases the vector
length from 2 to 4.\n- The instcombine debug log shows it visits the select and
then the shuffle, and immediately aborts when building the new select.\n\n3. Root
Cause Analysis:\nFoldOpIntoSelect assumes it can create a new select using the
existing condition SI->getCondition() and the newly folded true/false values
derived from applying the operation to each arm. However, SelectInst in LLVM
requires:\n- The condition to be i1 for scalar selects.\n- For vector selects,
the condition must be a vector of i1 with the same number of elements as the
result vector.\nIn this case, SI->getCondition() is <2 x i1>, but after folding
the shuffle into each arm, NewTV/NewFV are <4 x float>. SelectInst::Create is
called with mismatched vector lengths, triggering the assertion. There is no
guard in FoldOpIntoSelect to ensure the condition/result element counts match
when the operation changes vector length.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe need
to add an early bailout in FoldOpIntoSelect when folding would produce a select
whose result type has a different vector length than the select's condition.
Specifically, if SI's condition is a vector type, require that Op's result is
also a vector type with the same element count. If not, do not fold.\n\nEdit at
llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp lines 1696-1706 (right
after the existing checks that the select arms contain constants and the bool
select early return):\n\nInsert the following guard:\n\n  // If the select
condition is a vector, its length must match the\n  // result vector length of
the folded operation. Otherwise, creating\n  // a new select with the original
condition and the folded arm values\n  // would be invalid.\n  Type *OpTy =
Op.getType();\n  Type *CondTy = SI->getCondition()->getType();\n  if
(CondTy->isVectorTy()) {\n    auto *CondVTy = cast<VectorType>(CondTy);\n    if
(!OpTy->isVectorTy())\n      return nullptr;\n    auto *OpVTy =
cast<VectorType>(OpTy);\n    if (CondVTy->getElementCount() !=
OpVTy->getElementCount())\n      return nullptr;\n  }\n\nRationale:\n- This
prevents attempting to create a select with mismatched condition/result vector
lengths when the operation (e.g., shuffle) changes the vector length.\n- It
preserves existing, valid cases (scalar condition, or matching vector lengths),
and continues to allow folding of operations that do not change the vector
length.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by FoldOpIntoSelect creating an
invalid Select when folding a length-changing vector operation (shufflevector)
into a vector-select with a shorter condition. Adding a guard to bail out when
the condition is a vector and its element count differs from the folded
operation's result vector length prevents the invalid Select construction and
fixes the assertion. This maintains correctness without affecting other folding
opportunities.",
